<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Notes: Thespecies 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pedionis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pedionis (Pedionis) oeroe" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oeroe" subGenus="Pedionis">Pedionis (Pedionis) oeroe</taxonomicName>
should belong to the subgenus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pedionis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pedionis" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pedionis</taxonomicName>
by tegmina with only 2 subapical cells and veins dark fuscous multiannulate with whitish according to the original description, but no male genitalia manuscript (
<bibRefCitation author="Kirkaldy, GW" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Hawaiian Sugar Planters Association Experimental Station" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="1 - 20" title="Leafhoppers supplement (Hemiptera)." volume="3" year="1907">Kirkaldy 1907</bibRefCitation>
), the species 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pedionis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pedionis (Pedionis) thyia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thyia" subGenus="Pedionis">Pedionis (Pedionis) thyia</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from others by amount of anteapical cells (non-genitalic characters), therefore, the key 
<normalizedToken originalValue="don’t">don't</normalizedToken>
encompass these two species.
</paragraph>
